The ends of the bones in the knuckle are in very close proximity to each other, with a small space between them called the joint space. This space is filled with a very slippery fluid called synovial fluid. Once enough force is applied to your finger to overcome the adhesion or tension, there is a rapid increase in the size of joint space and a gas bubble forms in the joint space. The noise associated with cracking your knuckles is produced at the same time as the gas bubble forms. Once you let go of your finger, the gas bubble is reabsorbed by the fluid in the joint.
